,"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Killed in action Port Hudson, Louisiana, July 1864","body":"Levi H. Bartlett was killed on July 22, 1864 at the vicinity of Port Hudson Louisiana during the Civil War, at about age forty-two. He was serving as a private in Company B, Thirty-fifth Wisconsin Infantry — having enlisted from Wisconsin despite his Vermont origin. The Port Hudson siege was a critical Union operation to control the lower Mississippi River; the fortified Confederate position had finally fallen the year before, but skirmishes and casualties continued throughout 1864."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Vermont birth, Wisconsin enlistment, Louisiana death","body":"Levi H. Bartlett was born around 1822 in Vermont. By the time of his Civil War enlistment he was living in Wisconsin and joined the Thirty-fifth Wisconsin Infantry — the cross-country movement from his New England birthplace to his midwestern enlistment was characteristic of mid-nineteenth-century American settler migration. His death in Louisiana completed a Vermont-Wisconsin-Louisiana arc spanning his lifetime."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Left widow Elizabeth; buried Chalmette National","body":"Levi was survived by his widow Elizabeth Bartlett. He is buried at Chalmette National Cemetery in Saint Bernard Parish Louisiana — the federally-administered military cemetery for Union soldiers killed in the lower Mississippi River campaigns of the Civil War. The cemetery clusters thousands of Union dead from operations at Port Hudson, New Orleans, and surrounding theaters of the western Confederacy collapse."}],"slug":"levi-bartlett-1822"},"HD0952":{"id":"HD0952","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"d